CTF Writeup: Transformation
picoCTF | Reverse Engineering Challenge


-----------------------------------------------------------
WHAT WAS THIS CHALLENGE?
-----------------------------------------------------------

An encoded file called enc was provided. Opening it showed strange unreadable characters that looked like Chinese or other non-Latin symbols. The goal was to figure out the encoding and convert it back to readable ASCII text to reveal the flag.

The key concept: the file used UTF-16 encoding instead of the usual UTF-8 or ASCII. Each character was stored as 16 bits instead of 8, which is why it looked like gibberish.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 - Download the File
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used: wget https://challenge-files.picoctf.net/c_wily_courier/2f1e804dd3a62057e8693c0d543175b1ac8a2ea8becd1c658cc27b23f2385289/enc

What happened:
wget downloaded the encoded file into the current directory with the filename enc.

Remember: wget URL downloads any file from the internet directly into your terminal.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 - Verify the File is There
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used: ls

What happened:
ls listed the files in the current directory and confirmed enc was present and ready to work with.

Remember: always use ls to confirm your download worked before proceeding.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 3 - Read the Raw File
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used: cat enc

What happened:
The file contents looked like unreadable symbols and strange characters. This confirmed the file was encoded and not plain ASCII. The weird characters were actually UTF-16 encoded text where every two bytes represent one character instead of one byte per character.

This is called encoding — transforming readable text into a different format so it cannot be read directly.

Remember: if cat gives you unreadable garbage, that is a clue about the encoding. Do not panic, just figure out what encoding was used.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 4 - Open Python to Decode
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used: python3

What happened:
Python was opened in interactive mode to write a short decoding script step by step. Python has built-in tools for handling different text encodings.

Remember: python3 opens an interactive Python shell where you can type and run code line by line.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 5 - Read the File into a Variable
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command typed in Python: dumbIThere = open("enc").read()

What happened:
This opened the file enc, read all its contents, and saved them into a variable called dumbIThere. The variable now held the entire encoded text ready for processing.

Breaking it down:
open("enc") opens the file
.read() reads all its contents
dumbIThere = saves it into a variable

Remember: open("filename").read() is the standard Python way to read a file into a variable.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 6 - Create an Empty Variable for the Decoded Output
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command typed in Python: decoded = ''

What happened:
An empty string variable called decoded was created. This will be filled with the decoded characters one by one in the next step.

Note: use single quotes twice with nothing between them. This is an empty string, not a space.

Remember: always prepare a storage variable before building output in a loop.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 7 - Decode UTF-16 to ASCII
-----------------------------------------------------------

Commands typed in Python:

for a in dumbIThere:
  decoded = a.encode('utf-16be').decode('ascii')
  print(decoded)

What happened:
This loop went through every character in the encoded file one at a time. For each character it encoded it as UTF-16 big endian (utf-16be) and then decoded that as ASCII, converting the 16-bit characters back into standard readable text. The flag appeared character by character.

Important: the two spaces before decoded and print are required in Python. Python uses indentation to know what is inside the loop. Without the spaces it will throw an error.

Remember: in Python, indentation is not optional. Everything inside a loop must be indented consistently.


-----------------------------------------------------------
QUICK REFERENCE
-----------------------------------------------------------

wget URL                                 Download the file
ls                                       Confirm the file is there
cat enc                                  See the raw encoded contents
python3                                  Open Python interactive shell
dumbIThere = open("enc").read()          Read file into a variable
decoded = ''                             Create empty output variable
for a in dumbIThere:                     Loop through each character
  decoded = a.encode('utf-16be').decode('ascii')   Decode each character
  print(decoded)                         Print the result


